Start with [Event Sourcing](https://martinfowler.com/eaaDev/EventSourcing.html) by Martin Fowler. It's the most durable entry point because it focuses on the data model—capturing every change as an immutable event—rather than the specific message broker you're using.

Instead of just storing the current "snapshot" of your database, you store the sequence of things that happened. As Fowler explains, this gives you a built-in audit log; you don't just see the current state, you see the entire history of how the system arrived there. This shift is what enables features like "time travel" debugging and high-scale read models.

When you move beyond a single service, you'll need to understand the [Pattern: Saga](https://microservices.io/patterns/data/saga.html). Since you lose traditional ACID transactions in a distributed system, sagas coordinate multi-step workflows by chaining local transactions together. If a step fails, you trigger "compensating transactions" to undo the previous work manually.

```sdanswer
