      "estimate": "15m"
    },
    {
      "url": "https://microservices.io/patterns/data/saga.html",
      "description": "The reality of distributed logic. Learn why you need compensating transactions instead of rollbacks.",
      "estimate": "10m"
    },
    {
      "url": "https://microservices.io/patterns/data/transactional-outbox.html",
      "description": "The 'Outbox Pattern' solves the most common first bug: making sure your database update and your event message actually happen together.",
      "estimate": "5m"
    }
  ]
}
```

As you dig in, watch out for "dual writes"—it's tempting to just update your DB and send an event in the same function, but one will eventually fail while the other succeeds, leaving your system inconsistent.

Use **Postgres `FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED`** if your primary concern is atomic consistency between your database state and your job creation; choose **Amazon SQS** if your 10k/min bursts are likely to scale higher or if you need to decouple worker pressure from your primary database performance.

At 10,000 events per minute, Postgres is still well within its comfort zone, but it's the "frantic pace" of workers polling for jobs that creates the real risk. As detailed in [Transactionally Staged Job Drains in Postgres](https://brandur.org/job-drain), high-concurrency locking in Postgres can lead to performance degradation, especially if you have long-running transactions that keep the visibility map from being updated, forcing workers to scan through dead rows.

SQS handles the "thundering herd" of workers much more gracefully and includes primitives like [Dead-Letter Queues](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSSimpleQueueService/latest/SQSDeveloperGuide/sqs-dead-letter-queues.html) out of the box. The trade-off is that you lose the "Outbox Pattern" benefits: you can't wrap a database update and an SQS message in a single transaction. To bridge this gap, you'll need to implement [idempotency keys](https://brandur.org/idempotency-keys) so your workers can safely retry operations without side effects when the network or the queue inevitably hiccups.

```sdanswer
