        "Polled workers can stress DB CPU"
      ]
    },
    {
      "label": "Managed SQS",
      "bullets": [
        "Scales to massive throughput easily",
        "Built-in retries and DLQ support",
        "Requires idempotency handling",
        "No transactional atomicity with DB"
      ]
    }
  ]
}
```

If you want the best of both worlds, consider staging the jobs in a Postgres table and using a "drain" process to move them to SQS in bulk, which keeps your application logic atomic while offloading the worker-polling stress.

Use **SQS** if your priority is surviving the bursts without tuning your primary database; use **Postgres `SKIP LOCKED`** if transaction integrity between your data and your queue is worth the extra management overhead.

At 10k events per minute, Postgres can handle the load, but the "frantic pace" of workers competing for locks can cause performance to spiral, especially if you have long-running transactions elsewhere in your DB. [Transactionally Staged Job Drains in Postgres](https://brandur.org/job-drain) explains that while `SKIP LOCKED` is great for simple cases, heavy contention eventually forces a choice: either scale your DB vertically to handle the "noise" of the queue, or move the hot-path queueing to a tool like Redis or SQS.

SQS removes the contention problem from your database entirely and provides mature primitives like [Dead-Letter Queues](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSSimpleQueueService/latest/SQSDeveloperGuide/sqs-dead-letter-queues.html) for handling the failures that inevitably spike during bursts. The trade-off is the "dual-write" problem: if your DB update succeeds but the SQS push fails, your system is out of sync.

```sdanswer
