        "Must build your own retry/DLQ logic"
      ]
    },
    {
      "label": "Managed SQS",
      "bullets": [
        "Infinite scaling for 10k+ bursts",
        "Built-in DLQs and visibility timeouts",
        "Risk of DB/Queue inconsistency",
        "Adds network latency to every job push"
      ]
    }
  ]
}
```

If you choose SQS, your next challenge will be ensuring you don't process the same event twice after a network hiccup—read up on [Implementing Stripe-like idempotency keys in Postgres](https://brandur.org/idempotency-keys) to handle those edge cases safely.

Think of **Transactional Outbox** as the pattern for how your application handles intent, and **Change Data Capture (CDC)** as the infrastructure that implements it reliably.

For an agentic platform where an agent's "decision" to send an email must be durable, you cannot rely on a simple dual-write (updating your database and calling an email API/Kafka in one go). As [Reliable Microservices Data Exchange With the Outbox Pattern](https://debezium.io/blog/2019/02/19/reliable-microservices-data-exchange-with-the-outbox-pattern/) points out, you can't wrap a database and a message broker in a single transaction; if one fails after the other succeeds, your agent's state and its actual output will diverge.

The [Transactional outbox](https://microservices.io/patterns/data/transactional-outbox.html) pattern solves this by making the "send" an atomic part of your local database transaction—you write the email content to an `outbox` table in the same heartbeat that you update the agent's internal state. CDC is then the most robust way to get those messages out of the table. Instead of your app code polling the database (which adds load and latency), a CDC tool like Debezium tailors the database's write-ahead log (WAL) to stream those events to Kubernetes-hosted workers or a broker like Kafka.

```sdanswer
{
  "type": "tradeoff",
  "title": "Outbox Implementation Strategies",
  "options": [
    {
      "label": "Application Polling",
      "bullets": [
        "Easy to implement",
        "Adds query load to DB",
        "Higher latency for emails"
      ]
    },
    {
      "label": "CDC (Log-based)",
      "bullets": [
        "Near-zero DB overhead",
        "Sub-second latency",
        "Requires infrastructure (Debezium)"
      ]
    }
  ]
}
```

By using CDC on Kubernetes, you decouple the agent's execution from the delivery infrastructure, ensuring that once an agent "decides" to send an email, it's guaranteed to happen even if a pod restarts or a network partition occurs.

Before you commit to this, consider if your agents need to react to *any* change in state or just specific "send" events; CDC on every table can quickly turn into a firehose that's harder to manage than a dedicated outbox table.

Start with the "Red Book" (Readings in Database Systems) if you want the high-level architecture, but since you're looking to spend a weekend on the actual mechanics of how data hits the disk, start with [Database in Depth](https://www.oreilly.com/library/view/database-in-depth/0596100124/). While many guides jump straight to B-Trees, this resource grounds you in the relational model first—understanding the logical constraints of data makes it much clearer why physical implementations like Write-Ahead Logging (WAL) and Multiversion Concurrency Control (MVCC) have to exist the way they do.

If you want to see how these theories translate into specific data structures, [Redis University](https://university.redis.io/) offers a focused look at how structures like skip lists and hash maps operate in memory. For the "storage engine" side of your weekend, [MongoDB University](https://learn.mongodb.com/) has tracks on indexing and operational internals that explain how a database manages the trade-off between write throughput and read performance under load.

```sdanswer
