      "estimate": "4h"
    },
    {
      "url": "https://www.oreilly.com/library/view/database-in-depth/0596100124/",
      "description": "Deep dive into the storage engine level: WAL, concurrency control (MVCC), and the architecture of modern disk-based storage.",
      "estimate": "8h"
    }
  ]
}
```

As you read, pay close attention to how index maintenance impacts write operations—every new index you add makes reads faster but forces the database to do extra work for every `INSERT` and `UPDATE`.

You need to move past simple logging and adopt structured events and distributed tracing to capture the non-deterministic nature of agent loops. By treating each tool call as a span in a larger trace, you can use the "core analysis loop" described in [Observability Engineering](https://www.honeycomb.io/observability-engineering-oreilly-book) to iteratively verify hypotheses about why the agent is stuck or repeating itself.

Standard [APM traces](https://docs.newrelic.com/docs/apm/new-relic-apm/getting-started/introduction-apm/) are useful for mapping service dependencies, but for agents, you specifically need high-cardinality metadata—like the exact prompt version, the tool's return value, and the sequence index—attached to those traces. This allows you to differentiate between a healthy recursive search and a broken runaway loop by looking at the relationship between the entities and the data they pass.

```sdanswer
