  { "label": "Trace Context Propagation", "url": "https://docs.newrelic.com/docs/apm/new-relic-apm/getting-started/introduction-apm/" },
  { "label": "Instrumentation for On-Call", "url": "https://www.oreilly.com/library/view/distributed-systems-observability/9781492033431/" }
], "title": "Before you instrument tool calls"}
```

Once you have the traces, your next hurdle will be defining a "kill switch" that uses this telemetry to break the loop automatically when a depth or cost threshold is exceeded.

You'll want to use automated transaction tracing that captures each tool execution as a discrete span within the larger agentic loop. Since an agent is essentially [running tools in a loop](https://simonwillison.net/2025/Sep/30/designing-agentic-loops/) to reach a goal, debugging a "runaway" state requires seeing the sequence of tool inputs and outputs that triggered the next iteration.

Standard APM tools like those described in the [Introduction to New Relic APM](https://docs.newrelic.com/docs/apm/new-relic-apm/getting-started/introduction-apm/) are effective here because they provide low-overhead, automatic instrumentation. By treating each tool call as a "transaction," you can pinpoint exactly where the loop logic starts to drift or which specific "hotspot" is failing to return a terminating condition. This ensures that even if the agent enters an infinite loop, the individual traces are streamed to your collector rather than being lost when the process eventually hits a timeout or memory limit.

```sdanswer
{
  "type": "path",
  "links": [
    {
      "url": "https://simonwillison.net/2025/Sep/30/designing-agentic-loops/",
      "description": "Understand the loop-and-tool mental model so you know exactly which 'tool exit' points need instrumentation.",
      "estimate": "45m"
    },
    {
      "url": "https://docs.newrelic.com/docs/apm/new-relic-apm/getting-started/introduction-apm/",
      "description": "Learn how to use transaction traces to isolate performance hotspots and runaway tool calls in production.",
      "estimate": "1h"
    },
    {
      "url": "https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/architecture/patterns/bulkhead",
      "description": "Apply the Bulkhead pattern to isolate agent execution, preventing a runaway loop from consuming all system resources.",
      "estimate": "1h 30m"
    }
  ]
}
```

Once your tracing is live, look for "chatter"—sequences where the agent calls the same tool with near-identical parameters—as this is the most common signature of a loop that's lost its way.
